"Gravel J.-F., Luo Q., Boudreau D., Tang X.P., Chin S.L.","Sensing of halocarbons using femtosecond laser-induced fluorescence",2004,"Analytical Chemistry","76","16",,"4799","4805",,,10.1021/ac049425k,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-4043114781&partnerID=40&md5=bcec6c4d925c8eca9b8ef1476684e7af","Department of Chemistry, Ctr. d'Optique, Photonique et Laser, Université Laval, Québec, Que. G1K 7P4, Canada; Dept. of Phys., Phys. Eng. and Opt., Ctr. d'Optique, Photonique et Laser, Université Laval, Québec, Que. G1K 7P4, Canada","Gravel, J.-F., Dept. of Phys., Phys. Eng. and Opt., Ctr. d'Optique, Photonique et Laser, Université Laval, Québec, Que. G1K 7P4, Canada; Luo, Q., Dept. of Phys., Phys. Eng. and Opt., Ctr. d'Optique, Photonique et Laser, Université Laval, Québec, Que. G1K 7P4, Canada; Boudreau, D., Department of Chemistry, Ctr. d'Optique, Photonique et Laser, Université Laval, Québec, Que. G1K 7P4, Canada; Tang, X.P., Dept. of Phys., Phys. Eng. and Opt., Ctr. d'Optique, Photonique et Laser, Université Laval, Québec, Que. G1K 7P4, Canada; Chin, S.L., Dept. of Phys., Phys. Eng. and Opt., Ctr. d'Optique, Photonique et Laser, Université Laval, Québec, Que. G1K 7P4, Canada","A femtosecond laser-induced clean fluorescence technique was explored as a means to monitor halogenated alkanes in the atmosphere. Characteristic difluorocarbene radical (CF2) fluorescence in the UV-vis can be generated inside a femtosecond laser-induced filament for different halocarbons. We show that, due to different dissociation and excitation kinetics leading to fluorescence emission, it is possible to temporally resolve the characteristic fluorescence of CF2-containing halocarbons from that of background species, therefore enhancing the signal-to-noise ratio. Laboratory-scale experiments demonstrate the potential use of femtosecond laser-induced clean fluorescence for the remote sensing of halocarbons in the atmosphere. The combination of this detection strategy with LIDAR could allow the long-range monitoring of several atmospheric species with a single laser source, eventually leading to a better understanding of chemical and dynamic processes affecting global warming, ozone loss, tropospheric pollution, and weather prediction.",,"Fluorescence; Global warming; Lasers; Optical radar; Ultraviolet radiation; Femtosecond laser-induced fluorescence; Laser sources; Halogen compounds; halocarbon; analytic method; article; atmospheric diffusion; dissociation; excitation; femtosecond laser induced fluorescence technique; fluorescence analysis; greenhouse effect; laboratory test; laser; molecular dynamics; ozone layer; signal noise ratio; ultraviolet spectroscopy; weather; Calibration; Hydrocarbons, Fluorinated; Hydrocarbons, Halogenated; Kinetics; Lasers; Spectrometry, Fluorescence",,"difluorocarbene; Hydrocarbons, Fluorinated; Hydrocarbons, Halogenated",,,,"Sigrist, M.W., (1994) Air Monitoring by Spectroscopic Techniques, pp. 1-26. , Sigrist, M. W., Ed.; Wiley: New York; Molina, M.J., Rowland, F.S., (1974) Nature, 249, pp. 810-812; Stemmler, K., O'Doherty, S., Buchmann, B., Reimann, S., (2004) Environ. Sci. Technol., 38, pp. 1998-2004; Dolin, E.J., (1999) Light Met. Age, 57, pp. 56-67; Rhoderick, G., Chu, P., Dolin, E., Marks, J., Howard, T., Lytle, M., McKenzie, L., Altman, D., (2001) Fresenius' J. Anal. Chem., 370, pp. 828-833; Mangani, G., Berloni, A., Maione, A., (2003) J. Chromatogr., A, 988, pp. 167-175; Koch, J., Okruss, M., Franzke, J., Florek, S.V., Niemax, K., Becker-Ross, H., (2004) Spectrochim. Acta, Part B, 59, pp. 199-207; Abdillahi, M.M., (1990) J. Chromatogr. Sci., 28, pp. 613-616; Chu, P.M., (2003) Anal. Bioanal. Chem., 376, pp. 305-307; Hanst, P.L., Hanst, S.T., (1994) Air Monitoring by Spectroscopic Techniques, pp. 335-470. , Sigrist, M. W., Ed.; Wiley: New York; Gamble, H.A., Mackay, G.I., Karecki, D.R., Pisano, J.T., Schiff, H.I., (2001) Light Met., pp. 275-281; Haisch, C., Niessner, R., Matveev, O.I., Panne, U., Omenet